<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-20T18:36:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-20T18:36:00-05:00" n="926" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d926">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2840.</note>
                        <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-20T17:00:00-06:36">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 20, 1912—5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Railroad destroyed 40 miles south of Guadalajara, and frequent
                            revolutionary rumors throughout State of Jalisco. Increase of <pb facs="0838" n="722" xml:id="pg_722"/> local garrison urgent, and
                            representations have to-day been made to the Mexican Government. A
                            well-known American resident on the Isthmus of Tehauntepec reports a
                            state of affairs there which may at any moment result in a general
                            uprising dangerous to life and property. This has been informally
                            brought to the attention of Minister for Foreign Affairs, as have
                            conditions in Oaxaca, where a general uprising is feared.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>